---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About | Christopher Audretsch">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-8 md:py-16">
    <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-semibold text-text mb-8 md:mb-10">About</h1>

    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p>
        I studied computer science and philosophy at Indiana University and spent three years
        as a discretionary trader in Chicago. I now live in good old Berkeley.
      </p>

      <p>
        My main intellectual interests are memetics, ASI outcomes, and moral realism. I think
        the relationship between moral realism and the orthogonality thesis is extremely
        underrated in AI safety discussions: if moral realism is true, the orthogonality thesis
        is false. I'm working on a paper presenting an original view on moral realism that I
        think is very promising. It uses a concept I call "epistemic realms". The basic idea
        here is that different parts of reality require different modes of epistemic access to
        comprehend. In particular, many facts about consciousness require first person epistemic
        access, which is <em>not</em> available through the means of science.
      </p>

      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Email me at hello.audretsch at gmail.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
